The lush ponytail of my youth would have done a Californian cheerleader proud
Saturday night in a candlelit wine bar on a cobbled back street in York. A romantic evening at the end of a busy week.Adam puts down his glass and leans across the table to brush a stray eyelash from my cheek. A tender gesture, I think. He’ll pick it off and blow it gently from his fingers, making a wish for our future as he does so.‘Oh!’ he says, suddenly looking sheepish as I feel a sharp twinge.‘Mmm. It’s not an eyelash.’‘Well, what is it?’ I asked. ‘Fluff? Make-up?’Adam takes a large gulp of his Shiraz, clearly seeking Dutch courage (or oblivion?). He stares at me blankly, and I think I sense panic stirring somewhere inside him.‘Errr, it’s a hair. Quite a big one. Kind of browny-black. And it’s attached to your cheek,’ he tells me. There is a pause as he looks at me with . . . what? Pity? Contempt? I storm home, Adam silent in my slipstream, and make a beeline for my new five-times magnifying mirror and tweezers while he tries to make himself invisible, perhaps to spare me the humiliation of having to pluck out my first facial hair with an audience.This was a whole fortnight ago, which is a long time in menopause years. Since then my newest indignity is white, about a centimetre long and slightly curly. Strong as a steel guitar string and of similar girth, it snakes out of my right nostril and seems to be mocking me. More...
