I assumed at first that it must have blown into my nose from an outside source: it was only when I tried to brush it away that I realised it was home-grown.
Menopause, it seems, is the time of The Great Hair Migration. No one warned me about this, but where it was thick (head, underarms, eyebrows etc), it’s thinning; and where it never grew (nose and ears so far), it now accumulates. Hairs from my head accumulate in the plughole every time I have a bath or showerThe lush ponytail of my youth would have done a Californian cheerleader proud: now my mane looks like one of those sad strips of half-hair worn by ageing rockers.Hairs from my head accumulate in the plughole every time I have a bath or shower, and I’m reduced to removing newly arrived nasal hair with a light-up shaving wand which makes my nostrils look like mine again — instead of a fat, retired colonel’s.The late, great Hollywood writer and director Nora Ephron observed: ‘At a certain age, legs get less hairy. My guess is that by the time I’m 80, I will be able to handle any offending hair on my legs with two plucks of an eyebrow tweezer.’I know how she feels. Nora also said that the ‘fair, downy and inoffensive’ moustache of her youth became a force majeure when the menopause arrived.‘It was no longer dormant, incipient and threatening; it was now just plain there,’ she wrote. That’s one indignity I have so far been spared — but it can only be a matter of time before my beauty routine involves a full shave. Share or comment on this article
