James ‘Arg’ Argent is no stranger to yo-yo dieting and his ongoing struggle to maintain his weight has been publicly documented over the years that he has starred on The Only Way Is Essex.But now, the reality TV star is facing facts. With a BMI of 32 he is clinically obese and according to NHS guidelines needs to lose 5st 6lbs to reach a healthy weight. Taking drastic action to slim down, he is determined to lose weight and keep it off to prove his ‘haters’ wrong. Weight loss struggle: James Argent is on a mission to lose weight after hurtful Twitter comments about his size spurred him on
To kick-start his new fitness regime, he paid a visit to military-style bootcamp No 1 Boot Camp in Norfolk, where Made In Chelsea stars Binky Felstead and Spencer Matthews have also lost weight, where he lost 8lbs in three days but he still wants - and needs - to lose more.The 26-year-old, who weighed in at 17st 7lbs on arrival, said he is determined to shed the pounds and become the new heartthrob of his ITV2 reality show, which returns later this month. More...
Totes awkward! Spencer Matthews misses his red carpet moment at the Robocop premiere because his chauffeur gets caught up in tube strike traffic
Confessions of a Zumba virgin: 'My heart is beating, my legs are moving... just not in the same direction as everyone else's!
'I'm allergic to sex. It ruined my marriage': Woman who gets third-degree BURNS from intercourse tells her painful tale
He said: 'I want to lose another two stone before the next series of TOWIE. I want to be the new heartthrob. I don't want to be skinny but I want to come back and look handsome again.'Arg aims to shed his excess weight in record time and it won’t be the first time he’s proved his doubters and critics wrong. Having fun, Arg? James hit No. 1 Bootcamp in Norfolk, which has also helped fellow reality TV stars Binky Felstead and Spencer Matthews get into shape
In April 2012 he completed the Virgin London Marathon having only put in six weeks training. And as part of the Men’s Health Challenge last year, James lost a 2st in six weeks and 10 per cent of his body fat.In the past he has talked openly how hurtful he finds Twitter abuse about his weight. He said: 'What hurts is that I still get called the names every single day on Twitter. I don’t think people realise how much the criticism hurts sometimes. Lifestyle overhaul: Arg, pictured at his heaviest last year, is keen to lose weight and become the new TOWIE heartthrob
'The comedian Keith Lemon called me a fat b*****d recently. He said it in a funny way, but it still really upset me.'The reason Arg’s diets have failed in the past is simply down to his love of takeaways. Arg added: 'I just love food too much, I love takeaways.'
Favourite food: Arg has admitted to struggling with his weight because of his love of takeaways and unhealthy food
Nutritionist Nigel Penny warns Arg’s love of food and yo-yo weight loss is putting his health at serious risk. Nigel said: 'With a BMI of 32, James could be heading towards Type II Diabetes Mellitus and he is putting immense pressure on his heart. 'The takeaways he loves contain almost an average adult’s daily calorie recommendations in one meal.'They are high in salt and sugar and are often low in vitamins and minerals, including antioxidants, which help to protect against heart disease, insulin resistance and numerous cancers. Losing two stone in a matter of weeks is harmful to health.'Short-term effects include nausea, dizziness, headaches and long-term health issues could include osteoporosis. 'We should aim to lose no more than two pounds per week to give ourselves any chance of keeping off the weight. People who “yo-yo“ diet tend to put the weight back on incredibly quickly (and often put more on than before). 'On crash diets the body goes into a starvation protection mechanism, storing energy in an effort to protect itself if this ever happens again. Long way to go: While Arg has lost 8lbs, medics have warned there's more to lose in his quest to maintain a healthy lifestyle
'To maintain fat loss and avoid the negative health effects we should be realistic and encourage permanent and healthy lifestyle changes, rather than quick fixes. 'Our diets should be nutritionally balanced and including a variety of foods is essential in attempting to avoid deficiencies. We also need to consume the correct amount of calories for our age and sex, and for our individual activity levels.'Only time will tell if the only way is weight loss for Arg. As he was: Arg pictured, left, at a military style bootcamp this week and, right, when he first joined TOWIE in 2010
