From glory to gory in 114 days: Golden duck for Cook leaves Ashes triumph at Oval a distant memory
By
Paul Newman
PUBLISHED:
05:01 EST, 16 December 2013
| UPDATED:
22:04 EST, 16 December 2013
8
shares
98
View comments
It was just 114 days ago that Alastair Cook was holding the precious urn aloft in the gloom of The Oval, just over three months since a third successive series against Australia had been won and a fourth triumph was being keenly anticipated. How quickly those joyous Ashes scenes have turned to dust.What has happened here over three humiliating Tests has been a spectacular transformation in fortunes, with England having to face up to the harsh reality that they have been emphatically outplayed in every department.England may have held the Ashes since 2009 but no team have lost them quite as quickly after last winning them, back-to-back series proving that familiarity has bred not just contempt but a more defiant Australia.VIDEO Scroll down to watch Paul Newman: England's hold on the Ashes hanging by a thread Looking glum: Alastair Cook (left) and Kevin Pietersen sit on the dressing room balcony after their dismissals Going... Pietersen (right) attempts to hit a six off Nathan Lyon
Going... The England batsman looks as the ball goes high into the sky Gone: But he doesn't get enough on it and Ryan Harris pouches the ball at long on
Nervous glance: Pietersen looks at the ball's trajectory but Lyon (right) does not look too confident it'll be caught
Lyon King: The Australia spinner celebrates with George Bailey after dismissing Pietersen Trying to pull it back: Kevin Pietersen attempts to stay positive as Australia home in on victory Positive mental attitude: Pietersen took the attack to Australia... but did it once too often
Mighty England have not so much fallen as crashed. Ben Stokes was a ray of light amid the gloom on the fourth day of the third Test, but the Ashes have been torn from their grasp before Christmas and the most chastening of inquests is about to begin.Everywhere England look they will see painful confirmation that Australia, such a shambles in India this year and at the start of the English summer, have out-thought, out-fought and almost bullied them with superior plans and intent.If England arrived in Australia thinking it would be the same story as last time they were here, when it was they who had the gameplan and personnel to trample all over Australia, they have been sadly mistaken.As Andrew Strauss, the captain who led them to their glorious away triumph three years ago, said at the weekend, England came here expecting to fight the same war as in 2010 but instead discovered their old enemy had re-grouped. Now Australia have outfoxed England, leaving them looking like a tired team in decline.It has been the rudest of awakenings. If there was a degree of complacency, maybe even arrogance, about the way England greeted last summer’s 3-0 triumph then it has come back to bite them. They need to take a good long, hard look at themselves before they can move on from this.Sunday was a microcosm of all that has gone wrong in Brisbane, Adelaide and Perth — only more extreme. For the morning session of the fourth day was perhaps one of the worst England have known, certainly coming against an Australia side who stand poor comparison with the greats.From the moment Graeme Swann conceded 14 from the first over of the day it was carnage, 134 runs coming in just 17 overs with Shane Watson, who so seldom converts, helping himself to the easiest century he will score. Then, to compound the embarrassment, Jimmy Anderson, the leader of the England attack, was thumped for 28 by George Bailey — yes, George Bailey — to equal the record scored off one Test over. Michael Clarke declared with England’s spirits on the floor and they got lower immediately after.When Alastair Cook was bowled first ball of the England second innings, a golden duck in his 100th Test, it was possible to argue that — right there, right then — English cricket had never been lower. Paul Newman: England's hold on the Ashes hanging by a thread
What a start! Alastair Cook is bowled by Ryan Harris with the first ball of England's second innings Castled: Cook seems disbelieving after the ball evades his bat and crashes into the stumps Brilliant ball. Harris's delivery to Cook first up was nigh-on unplayable, as our Hawk-Eye graphic shows
Don't look back in anger: Cook looks back at his stumps, minus the bails, and then trudges off disconsolately Jumping for joy: Harris is delirious after bowling Cook with the first delivery of the innings
Jubilation: The Australian fielders go wild after the wicket makes it a dream start to England's second innings High fives: Cook leaves the field as Harris takes the acclaimAt least when they were whitewashed in 2006-07 they were playing one of the greatest teams. It could have been over by tea but thankfully England rallied, in the main through the promising and plucky Stokes, who finished in sight of England’s first century of the series. Compared to Australia’s seven, that is the most damning statistic of all. Wheels come off: Michael Carberry walks back to the pavilion after being trapped lbw by Shane Watson
Plumb: Watson's delivery to Carberry is hitting middle and the batsman is rightly given out Spectacular: Brad Haddin (left) dives to his right to take a superb catch to dismiss Joe Root
He's uprooted one: Mitchell Johnson celebrates after having Joe Root caught behind
Bad review: Root (centre) asks the third umpire to have a look at his dismissal but the decision is upheld Getting it right: Pietersen gets down the pitch and hits Lyon for six over long on The fallen: (from left) Root, Carberry, Cook and Pietersen on from the balcony after their dismissals
Close call: Root (left) was given not out after this lbw shout and it was upheld following an Australian review Appealing habit: The Australia slip cordon go up for lbw against Root (centre) Digging in: Root drives at the ball after coming in after Cook's very early dismissal Caught out: Brad Haddin attempts to take a ball that deviates off one of the huge cracks on the pitch
Watch out: Steve Smith and David Warner are obviously keen and collide while fielding Laughing it off: Smith and Warner share a chuckle after their fielding mishapBRUTAL BAILEYGeorge Bailey's assault on James Anderson equalled the highest number of runs scored in one Test over. Here is the top 10 28 G Bailey (Aus) off J Anderson (Eng) Perth 2013-1428 B Lara (WI) off R Peterson (SA) Johannesburg 2003-0427 Shahid Afridi (Pak) off Harbhajan Singh (Ind) Lahore 2005-0626 C McMillan (NZ) off Younis Khan (Pak) Hamilton 2000-0126 B Lara (WI) off Danish Kaneria (Pak) Multan 2006-0726 M Johnson (Aus) off P Harris (SA) Johannesburg 2008-0925 AB de Villiers (SA) off A McDonald (Aus) Cape Town 2008-0924 A Roberts (WI) off I Botham (Eng) Port-of-Spain 1980-8124 S Patil (Ind) off B Willis (Eng) Old Trafford 198224 I Botham (Eng) off D Stirling (NZ) The Oval 1986
Pietersen thrills and infuriates in equal measure and England will have to look at his dedication when the dust settles on this debacle for they will need proof that he really is committed to the next tour of South Africa.But they will be loath to throw out someone so talented without an adequate replacement and it should be said Ian Bell was equally culpable in trying to repeat the uppercut that also brought him six when he fell to Peter Siddle. It seems both England’s big guns misfired with their shot selection, so it would be unfair to single out Pietersen for that.The debate as to where England go from here can wait for another day but for now the sad truth is they are not a potentially great team any more.The senior batsmen are culpable for that and for England’s biggest problems here. And that is why scrutiny will rest on Kevin Pietersen, who will inevitably have his desire questioned after holing out again trying to hit Nathan Lyon for a second
straight six in consecutive overs. Instead
he gave away his fifth legside catch in six innings, which is simply not good enough for a batsman who aspires to greatness. Cruel cut: Ian Bell tries an upper cut but feathers the ball through to Haddin and is given out after a review
A good review: Siddle and his Australia team-mates roar after Bell's not out decision is overturned
Hitting out: Bell carves the ball through the off-side
Fully focused: Ian Bell keeps his eyes on the ball and drives it through the covers Nifty fifty: Bell raises his bat after scoring his half century
England on their knees: But Bell tried to stay positive and score when he could
On his marks: Bell looks as if he is ready to set off for a run during his innings Encouraging: Ben Stokes salutes his half century and ended the day on 72 not out
Giving them short shrift: Ben Stokes pulls the ball away
Fired-up Stokes: England's No 6 plays an expansive shot into the leg-side Steaming in: Johnson in his delivery stride as he attempts to bowl England out Declaration of intent: Clarke signals for the Australia batsmen to come in after they extended their lead to over 500 It's a wonderful life: George Bailey plays his shots with glorious abandon at the end of the Australia innings Shambles: Ian Bell (right) and James Anderson almost collide trying to take a catch - which Bell drops anyway Super effort: Tim Bresnan takes a stunning catch on the long-on boundary...
Unlucky: But Bresnan's momentum takes him backwards, and unfortunately he falls over the rope (below)
Light relief: Ben Stokes takes the congratulations after taking the wicket of Steve Smith
Roar talent: Shane Watson celebrates reaching his century after walloping the England attack around
On the front foot: Watson hit out on the fourth morning on the way to his hundred
Pushing the boundaries: There were plenty of fours and sixes in Watson's century
